<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Whirlpool is the largest appliance brand in America. We service it from all 8 branches.</h2>

    <p>Whirlpool Corporation is the largest major-appliance manufacturer in the world, headquartered in Benton Harbor, Michigan, with major US manufacturing in Ohio, Oklahoma, and Iowa. In our five-county SoCal service area, Whirlpool sits in more rental kitchens, production-builder homes, and laundry rooms than any other single brand. The Whirlpool platform also underpins three of its sister brands, Maytag, KitchenAid, and Amana, which means a tech who knows Whirlpool inside and out also services most of those calls without missing a step. (JennAir, Whirlpool's luxury tier, requires specific built-in training; we dispatch it accordingly.)</p>

    <p>Two Whirlpool-specific service realities shape how we approach every call. First, the <strong>2018-2021 wire-harness class action</strong> covers Whirlpool, Maytag, KitchenAid, and JennAir Side-by-Side and French Door refrigerators built in that window, wires routing through the freezer-side door hinge fatigue and break from repeated door movement, causing intermittent or complete failure of the ice maker, ice dispenser, water dispenser, and control panel. Settlement claim deadline is <strong>November 2, 2026</strong>. We verify class-action eligibility on diagnostic visits, if the unit qualifies and the claim window is still open, we route the customer to file before paying out-of-pocket. Second, Whirlpool's <strong>laundry product split</strong> between Cabrio (high-efficiency top-load) and Duet (front-load) creates two very different service trees, Cabrio's lid lock and suspension rod issues are different from Duet's drain pump, door boot, and bearing service patterns. We carry both lines of parts on the truck.</p>

    <p>This page covers Whirlpool repair across all major appliance categories. Every service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM parts where we can, and an honest written quote before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 REFRIGERATOR -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Whirlpool refrigerator repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Whirlpool refrigerators, wire-harness class action, ice maker, control board.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Whirlpool refrigerators dominate the mid-tier market, Side-by-Side (WRS series), French Door (WRF series), bottom-freezer (WRB), top-freezer (WRT), and Counter-Depth (WRX) variants. KitchenAid (KRFC, KRSF) and Maytag (MFI, MFF) refrigerators share most of the same parts platform with Whirlpool branding differences. The service tree splits across three main areas.</p>

    <div class="callout-box">
      <h3>Wire-harness class action (2018-2021 manufacture window)</h3>
      <p>Whirlpool, Maytag, KitchenAid, and JennAir Side-by-Side and French Door refrigerators built between 2018 and 2021 are covered by a class action settlement for a documented wire-harness defect. The wires routing through the freezer-side door hinge fatigue and break from repeated door open-close cycles, causing the ice maker, ice dispenser, water dispenser, and control panel to fail intermittently or stop working entirely. <strong>Claim deadline is November 2, 2026</strong>. If your unit was manufactured in this window and shows any of the symptoms, the repair likely qualifies for settlement coverage rather than out-of-pocket payment. We verify model, serial, and manufacture date on the diagnostic visit and tell you whether to file the claim or proceed with us. Honest first.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond the class-action question, Whirlpool refrigerator service tree centers on three areas:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Ice maker (year 4-7):</strong> Whirlpool ice maker assemblies (most common: WPW10882923 modular type) have a typical 5-7 year service life. Common failure modes: optics fault (low-ice condition not detected), water inlet valve not opening, motor module mechanical failure, water inlet tube freeze-up. Replacement $245-$385.</li>
      <li><strong>Water inlet valve + dispenser system (year 5-9):</strong> Solenoid wear on dual-coil water valves causing partial fills, slow water dispensing, or full failure. $185-$285 replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Main control board (year 6-10):</strong> Less prone to failure than GE boards but still a wear item, especially after power surges common during SoCal heat-wave grid events. Replacement $345-$525.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket (year 8-12):</strong> Especially in coastal homes (Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Newport Beach) where salt air accelerates rubber degradation. Replacement $180-$280.</li>
      <li><strong>Defrost system (year 7-11):</strong> Defrost heater, thermostat, or sensor failure causing frost buildup or no-cool. Diagnostic separates which component; $185-$345 replacement depending on item.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Whirlpool side-by-side and French Door units in the 2018-2021 class action window are the most-reported service item in our current Whirlpool refrigerator mix, we screen every refrigerator service call against the eligibility criteria before quoting paid work.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 LAUNDRY -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Whirlpool laundry repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Whirlpool washers and dryers, Cabrio, Duet, and the F01 / F1 / F7 code tree.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Whirlpool has the largest US laundry installed base of any single brand. Three distinct families dominate our service mix: Cabrio (high-efficiency top-load), Duet (front-load), and the legacy direct-drive top-loaders still in service in older homes. Each has a different service tree.</p>

    <p><strong>Cabrio top-load washers (WTW-series)</strong> launched in the mid-2000s as Whirlpool's HE top-load entry, most are impeller-driven (no agitator), with a glass lid and electronic controls. Service patterns:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Lid lock / lid switch (year 3-6):</strong> Most common Cabrio failure. Won't start, won't enter spin, or stops mid-cycle. Replacement $145-$215.</li>
      <li><strong>Suspension rod kit (year 9+):</strong> Excessive vibration on spin cycles. Cabrio top-load uses suspension rods; when one wears, basket starts walking. $245-$385 for the kit.</li>
      <li><strong>Drive belt + actuator (year 5-8):</strong> Won't agitate or won't shift between agitate and spin. $185-$345.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain pump (year 6-9):</strong> Won't drain, leaves clothes wet. $245-$385.</li>
      <li><strong>Main control board / actuator combination (year 8-12):</strong> Diagnostic-distinct from mechanical drive failures.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Duet front-load washers (WFW-series)</strong> share architecture with most front-load washers across the industry, drum on bearing, door boot, drain pump, CCU control board. Service tree:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Drain pump (year 5-8):</strong> Foreign objects (coins, hair, lint) are the most common cause; pump replacement when worn. $245-$385.</li>
      <li><strong>Door boot (year 8-10):</strong> Tearing, mold ingress, or detergent-buildup damage. $285-$425.</li>
      <li><strong>Bearing + drum seal (year 8-12):</strong> Grinding sound during spin cycles. Replaced as a set; replacing only the bearing without the seal will fail again within months. $585-$880 with labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Main control board / CCU (year 8-11):</strong> F1, F11, F26, or no-power symptoms. $345-$525.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Whirlpool dryers (Duet WED, Cabrio WED, base WED)</strong> are middle-of-the-pack reliability with one specific code worth noting. The <strong>F01 error</strong> on Whirlpool dryers indicates a CCU (main control board) internal short, usually triggered by a power surge or extended power outage. About 15% clear with a 5-10 minute power-cycle reset; the rest require CCU replacement ($345-$525). Standard service items: thermal fuse blown from vent blockage (always inspect the vent before replacing the fuse, thermal fuse alone fails again within weeks if vent isn't cleared), heating element burnout at year 8-12, drum belt + idler pulley wear at year 6-9, thermistor drift causing intermittent heating. Gas dryers add gas valve coil failure at year 9-12.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 OTHER APPLIANCES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Other Whirlpool appliances</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Whirlpool dishwashers, ranges, ovens, microwaves.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Whirlpool's appliance breadth covers every kitchen and laundry category in the US market. Service tree for non-laundry, non-refrigeration items follows mostly conventional patterns, Whirlpool engineering tends toward reliability over feature-density, which makes parts and diagnostic procedures consistent across model generations.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Whirlpool Dishwashers (WDT, WDF, Quiet Partner)</h3>
        <p>Mid-tier dishwasher reliability across the WDT and WDF series. Common service: drain pump, water inlet valve, control board, door latch (year 6-9), heating element/thermistor. KitchenAid dishwashers (KDTM, KDFE) share platform with premium Whirlpool models with cosmetic differences.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Whirlpool Ranges (WFG gas, WFE electric)</h3>
        <p>Gas and electric freestanding ranges in mid-tier. Common service: surface igniter (gas), bake/broil element (electric), oven temperature sensor, control board, oven door hinge + spring. F-codes diagnosed through standard Whirlpool tree.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Whirlpool Wall Ovens (WOS, WOC double)</h3>
        <p>Single (WOS) and double (WOC) wall ovens. Less common than freestanding ranges in our service mix but consistent with the same parts platform, bake/broil element, sensor, control board, latch motor on self-clean models.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Whirlpool Microwaves (WMH, WMC, Velos)</h3>
        <p>Over-the-range (WMH) and countertop (WMC) units. Common service: door switch (3-switch system; one fails and microwave won't start), magnetron, turntable motor, charcoal/grease filters (consumables). Velos speed-cook (convection + microwave) variants add convection element complexity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Whirlpool Cooktops (WCG, WCE, WCI)</h3>
        <p>Gas (WCG), electric coil (WCE), induction (WCI). Common service: surface igniter (gas), burner switch, infinite-switch control (electric), induction module (induction). Induction cooktop repair is specialty work; we dispatch it accordingly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>KitchenAid &amp; Maytag (Whirlpool family)</h3>
        <p>KitchenAid kitchen appliances (KRFC refrigerators, KDTM dishwashers, KDPE/KFC ranges) are positioned as the premium tier of the Whirlpool platform with shared parts and diagnostic procedures. Maytag laundry (MVWB Bravos top-load, MHW front-load, MED dryers) shares Whirlpool engineering with different cosmetic trim. Same parts network, same service depth.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 ERROR CODES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Whirlpool error codes decoded</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What the codes on your Whirlpool actually mean.</h2>

    <p>Whirlpool's error codes vary by appliance and platform, F-codes dominate washer, dryer, oven, and dishwasher displays. The common ones we translate on every service visit:</p>

    <div class="error-table">
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F01 (dryer)</strong>, Main control board (CCU) internal short. Power-cycle reset clears 15%; balance need CCU replacement.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F1 (washer)</strong>, Main control board / program fault. Most common Cabrio washer board failure code.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F7 E1 (washer)</strong>, Motor speed sensor fault. Hall sensor, harness, or motor itself.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F11 / F26 / F2X (Duet washer)</strong>, Door lock / serial communication / CCU faults.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>SD (washer)</strong>, Excess suds detected. Switch to HE detergent and reduce dose.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>LD (washer)</strong>, Long drain, water not draining within window. Pump, hose, or filter.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>UL (washer)</strong>, Unbalanced load. Redistribute and restart; persistent UL = suspension rod or bearing.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F1 (oven/range)</strong>, Control board watchdog fault. Reset clears 10%; balance is board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F2 (oven)</strong>, Oven over-temperature. Sensor or board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F3 / F4 (oven)</strong>, Oven temperature sensor open (F3) or shorted (F4).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>PF (refrigerator/dryer)</strong>, Power failure / interruption. Informational on first occurrence; persistent = board.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>HE (dishwasher)</strong>, Heating element fault. Element or thermistor.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F8 E4 (dishwasher)</strong>, Water level / inlet valve fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F9 E1 (dishwasher)</strong>, Drain pump fault. Pump, sensor, or harness.</div>
    </div>

    <p>Reset procedure for any Whirlpool appliance showing an error: kill the breaker for a full 5-10 minutes (longer than most appliances need to fully discharge filter capacitors). About 10-15% of error codes clear at this step at no parts cost. If the code returns, that's the diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 MODELS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
